# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: manufacturing-execution-systems
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/isa-95] There are 5 parts of the ISA-95 standard.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/isa-95] The models help define boundaries between the enterprise systems and the control systems.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/isa-95] They help address questions like which tasks can be executed by which function and what information must be exchanged between applications.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/isa-95] Here is a Archived 2014-11-05 at the Wayback Machine.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/isa-95] Within production areas activities are executed and information is passed back and forth.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/isa-95] The standard provides reference models for production activities, quality activities, maintenance activities and inventory activities.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/manufacturing-execution-system] MES creates the "as-built" record, capturing the data, processes and outcomes of the manufacturing process.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/manufacturing-execution-system] This can be especially important in regulated industries, such as food and beverage or pharmaceutical, where documentation and proof of processes, events and actions may be required.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/manufacturing-execution-system] As of 2025, the manufacturing execution systems are shifting from rigid, monolithic on-premise software to modular, cloud-connected platforms.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/manufacturing-execution-system] "Manufacturing execution systems [help] create flawless manufacturing processes and provide real-time feedback of requirement changes", and provide information at a single source.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/manufacturing-execution-system] A wide variety of systems arose using collected data for a dedicated purpose.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/manufacturing-execution-system] Further development of these systems during the 1990s introduced overlap in functionality.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/manufacturing-execution-system] Then the Manufacturing Enterprise Solutions Association International (MESA) introduced some structure by defining 11 functions that set the scope of MES.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/manufacturing-execution-system] In 2000, the ANSI/ISA-95 standard merged this model with the Purdue Reference Model (PRM).
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/manufacturing-execution-system] A functional hierarchy was defined in which MES were situated at Level 3 between ERP at Level 4 and process control at Levels 0, 1, 2.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/manufacturing-execution-system] With the publication of the third part of the standard in 2005, activities in Level 3 were divided over four main operations: production, quality, logistics and maintenance.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/manufacturing-execution-system] Between 2005 and 2013, additional or revised parts of the ANSI/ISA-95 standard defined the architecture of an MES into more detail, covering how to internally distribute functionality and what information to exchange internally as well as externally.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/manufacturing-execution-system] Over the years, international standards and models have refined the scope of such systems in terms of activities.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/manufacturing-execution-system] MES integrates with ISA-95 (previous Purdue Reference Model, “95”) with multiple relationships.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/manufacturing-execution-system] The collection of systems acting on the ISA-95 Level 3 can be called manufacturing operations management systems (MOMS).
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/manufacturing-execution-system] Apart from an MES, there are typically laboratory information management system (LIMS), warehouse management system (WMS) and computerized maintenance management system (CMMS).
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/manufacturing-execution-system] Examples of systems acting on ISA-95 Level 4 are product lifecycle management (PLM), enterprise resource planning (ERP), customer relationship management (CRM), human resource management (HRM), and process development execution system (PDES).
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/manufacturing-execution-system] In many cases, middleware enterprise application integration (EAI) systems are being used to exchange transaction messages between MES and Level 4 systems.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/manufacturing-execution-system] A common data definition, B2MML, has been defined within the ISA-95 standard to link MES systems to these Level 4 systems.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/manufacturing-execution-system] Systems acting on ISA-95 Level 2 are supervisory control and data acquisition (SCADA), programmable logic controllers (PLC), distributed control systems (DCS) and building automation systems (BAS).
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/manufacturing-execution-system] Most MES systems include connectivity as part of their product offering.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/manufacturing-execution-system] Direct communication of plant floor equipment data is established by connecting to the PLC.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/manufacturing-execution-system] Often, plant floor data is first collected and diagnosed for real-time control in a DCS or SCADA system.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/manufacturing-execution-system] In this case, the MES systems connect to these Level 2 systems for exchanging plant floor data.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/manufacturing-execution-system] The industry standard for plant floor connectivity has evolved from OLE for Process Control (OPC) to OPC Unified Architecture (OPC-UA).
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/manufacturing-execution-system] Unlike its predecessor, OPC-UA is platform-independent, allowing it to run on Linux and embedded devices while offering robust security models.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/manufacturing-execution-system] In modern Industry 4.0 architectures, MES connectivity often extends beyond the traditional hierarchy.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/manufacturing-execution-system] Systems increasingly utilize IIoT protocols like MQTT (often with Sparkplug B) to transmit lightweight data to cloud-based analytics platforms, creating a hybrid architecture where OPC-UA handles complex machine data and MQTT handles rapid telemetry.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Measuring OEE is a manufacturing best practice.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/overall-equipment-effectiveness] By measuring OEE and the underlying losses, important insights can be gained on how to systematically improve the manufacturing process.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Technically, OEE is an effective metric for identifying and visualizing losses, and steering the improvement of the effectiveness of manufacturing equipment by eliminating 'waste'.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Socially, OEE can provide a common language for groups speaking in different 'languages' such as shop floor (units), managers (money) or planners (time).
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/overall-equipment-effectiveness] The term OEE was first mentioned in Seiichi Nakajima's book 'TPM Tenkai' in 1982.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/overall-equipment-effectiveness] OEE was described as a central part of the Total Productive Maintenance methodology.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/overall-equipment-effectiveness] It is based on the Harrington Emerson way of thinking regarding labor efficiency.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/overall-equipment-effectiveness] 100% OEE is considered to be a theoretical reference point where a machine would be permanently running, at its theoretical maximal speed, producing only good products.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Anything hindering this is considered to be a 'loss'.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/overall-equipment-effectiveness] When running: Is the machine running at theoretical maximal speed?
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Is the output meeting its specifications?
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/overall-equipment-effectiveness] The first question leads to the 'availabilty rate' of the equipment, the second one to the 'performance rate' and the third one to the 'quality rate'.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/overall-equipment-effectiveness] in this way, a cascade of effectiveness and effectiveness losses arises.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/overall-equipment-effectiveness] The quality rate refers to a part of the performance (the part that there was 'speed', the other part is lost in the performance rate).
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/overall-equipment-effectiveness] The Performance rate refers to part of the availability (the time there was output - the other part is lost in the availability rate).
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Each of the three components of the OEE points to an aspect of the process that can be targeted for improvement.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/overall-equipment-effectiveness] OEE may be applied to any individual equipment or line.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/overall-equipment-effectiveness] This tool also allows for drilling down for very specific analysis, such as a particular Time frame, Shift, Team or any of several other parameters.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Although the performance of a particular product can be determined from OEE data, OEE cannot be calculated for that product because this would require that all downtime (availability losses) should be correlated to specific products.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/overall-equipment-effectiveness] OEE focusses on the 'if not' in the equations: Where did potential effectiveness got lost?
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/overall-equipment-effectiveness] These 'losses' of effectiveness are being subdivided further into what is known as the 'Six Big Losses' to OEE.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/overall-equipment-effectiveness] In order to make this more universally applicable and also to better reflect the financial impact of the losses, the original six big losses were later adjusted slightly.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/overall-equipment-effectiveness] The reason for identifying the losses in these categories is so that specific countermeasures can be applied to reduce the loss and improve the overall OEE.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Multiplying the three underlying grades AxPxQ results in a percentage value that indicates the proportion of the scheduled machine running time during which production actually met the quality criteria.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/overall-equipment-effectiveness] This value is always well below 100%, as 100% is a theoretical value.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Even if a system runs continuously at maximum speed without causing a single defect, it will for example still need to be serviced at some point.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Alternatively, the OEE as a number could be calculated by dividing the minimum time needed to produce the parts under optimal conditions by the actual time needed to produce the parts.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/overall-equipment-effectiveness] However, in this way the losses are no longer known, meaning the most important part of OEE is missing.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/overall-equipment-effectiveness] The value range for OEE is between 0% and 100%.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/overall-equipment-effectiveness] If an effectiveness level of more than 100% is displayed, this indicates an error in the definition.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/overall-equipment-effectiveness] The Availability portion of the OEE Metric represents the percentage of scheduled time (also referred to as 'loading time') that the equipment is available to operate.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/overall-equipment-effectiveness] A given machine is scheduled to run for an 8-hour (480-minute) shift with a 30-minute break, during which the machine is being stopped, and there is a breakdown of 60 minutes.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/overall-equipment-effectiveness] During the scheduled operating time of 480 minutes, the machine was waiting 30 min. because of the break and 60 minutes because it broke down.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/overall-equipment-effectiveness] The performance rate represents the ratio between the theoretical maximum speed of the machine and its actual speed.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Performance can only be calculated when there is output; thus during actual running time.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/overall-equipment-effectiveness] While the actual performance can be measured, it is often difficult in operational practice to obtain the theoretical maximum speed as a reference value.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/overall-equipment-effectiveness] The technical data provided by the machine manufacturer does not usually correspond to the theoretically possible maximum values, e.g. to avoid complaints or for other reasons.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Defining a too low maximum speed will become visible when the performance goes above 100%, which is undesirable.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Ultimately, the goal of OEE is to reveal all potential.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/overall-equipment-effectiveness] It is a good practice to calculate the maximum value based on physical limits, e.g., a calculation of heat transfer, the power of a motor, or the fall speed of a product.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/overall-equipment-effectiveness] If that fails, the concept of "best demonstrated cycle time" has proven itself.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/overall-equipment-effectiveness] This involves determining the production speeds of products from the past and increasing the highest production speed by a margin of 20%.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Defining this as 100% performance may lead to a structurally too low OEE, however it will visualize any potential loss on the performance.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/overall-equipment-effectiveness] The factor 1 (100%) now represents a peak value that is never exceeded, even for a short time.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/overall-equipment-effectiveness] For systems that only manufacture one or a few products, calculating the performance factor is simple.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/overall-equipment-effectiveness] If a large number of different products with different maximum speeds are run on one system (multi-product companies), the effort required to determine the maximum speed can be high and the performance should be calculated correctly using a weighted average.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/overall-equipment-effectiveness] A given equipment is scheduled to run for an 8-hour (480-minute) and has 90 min downtime.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/overall-equipment-effectiveness] The equipment produces 242 Total Units during the shift.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Note: The basis is Total Units, not Good Units.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/overall-equipment-effectiveness] The Performance metric does not penalize for Quality.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/overall-equipment-effectiveness] The Quality portion of the OEE Metric represents the Good Units produced as a percentage of the Total Units produced.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/overall-equipment-effectiveness] The Quality Metric is a pure measurement of Process Yield that is designed to exclude the effects of Availability and Performance.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/overall-equipment-effectiveness] The losses due to defects and rework are called *quality losses*.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/overall-equipment-effectiveness] The calculations of OEE may not seem to be particularly complicated, but care must be taken as to standards that are used as the basis.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/overall-equipment-effectiveness] In order to visualize all losses, it is crucial to use the right 'configuration' of the metric.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Definitions — for parts — of the OEE can be found in ISO 22400-2:2014. and VDI 3423:2011-08 (2011) These definitions are not standardized for all industries and are individually tailored to the respective company in its application.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Furthermore, the ISO 22400 standard presents two different OEE versions that appear to be inconsistent with one another, the first of which – in the standard's normative section – contains no reference to or connection with the original Nakajima's Total Productive Maintenance (TPM) model.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/overall-equipment-effectiveness] To resolve this ambiguity, academic literature provides a comprehensive classification framework that maps the standard's time elements to the traditional OEE formula, ensuring consistency between the ISO standard and established industrial practices.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/overall-equipment-effectiveness] This to OEE dedicated standard aims for the visualisation of all effectiveness losses on any manufacturing equipment, being unabigiously clear to production personnel.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/overall-equipment-effectiveness] The standard uses the same logic and uniform terminology for any type of equipment.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/overall-equipment-effectiveness] In order to calculate OEE, operational data needs to be acquired from the production process.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/overall-equipment-effectiveness] This needs to reflect 'what happened' on one hand, and 'what did not happen' (the losses) on the other hand.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Depending on the systems or products, it can be difficult to collect the basic data required to determine the key figure.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Many companies therefore rely on special software for data collection.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/overall-equipment-effectiveness] The goal of TPM (Total Productive Maintenance) as set out by Seiichi Nakajima, is "The continuous improvement of OEE by engaging all those that impact on it in small group activities".
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/overall-equipment-effectiveness] To achieve this, the TPM toolbox sets out a Focused improvement tactic to reduce each of the six types of OEE loss.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/overall-equipment-effectiveness] For example, the Focused improvement tactic to systematically reduce breakdown risk sets out how to improve asset condition and standardise working methods to reduce human error and accelerated wear.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Zero Failure Management provides a profound structure to achieve this.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Combining OEE with Focused improvement converts OEE from a lagging to a leading indicator that can be used to guide performance management priorities.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/overall-equipment-effectiveness] The first Focused improvement stage of OEE improvement is to achieve a stable OEE, i.e. one which varies at around 5% from the mean for a representative production sample.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/overall-equipment-effectiveness] This indicates that the asset performance is stable and not affected by variability in equipment wear rates and working methods.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/overall-equipment-effectiveness] The second stage of OEE improvement (optimisation) is meant to remove chronic losses.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/overall-equipment-effectiveness] As the TPM process delivers these gains through small cross functional improvement teams, the process of OEE improvement should also raise front line team engagement, problem ownership, collaboration and skill levels.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/overall-equipment-effectiveness] This combination of OEE as a KPI, TPM Focused improvement tactics and front line team engagement is intended to make the gains sustainable and deliver the TPM goal of year on year improvement in OEE.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Zero Failure Management helps significantly to achieve this.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/overall-equipment-effectiveness] OEE measurement is also commonly used as a key performance indicator (KPI) in conjunction with lean manufacturing efforts.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/overall-equipment-effectiveness] To achieve the main goal of Lean, creating flow, individual pieces of equipment need to be fully reliable and in tune.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/overall-equipment-effectiveness] TEEP, therefore, reports the 'bottom line' effectiveness of manufacturing equipment.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/overall-equipment-effectiveness] To calculate the Total Effective Equipment Performance(TEEP), the OEE is multiplied by a fourth component: Loading.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/overall-equipment-effectiveness] The Loading rate of the TEEP Metric represents the percentage of time that the equipment is scheduled to operate compared to the total Calendar Time that is available.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/overall-equipment-effectiveness] The Loading Metric is a pure measurement of Schedule effectiveness and is designed to exclude the effects how well that equipment may perform.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/overall-equipment-effectiveness] A given equipment is scheduled to run 5 Days per Week, 24 Hours per Day.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/overall-equipment-effectiveness] For a given week, the Total Calendar Time is 7 Days at 24 Hours.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/overall-equipment-effectiveness] The advantage of OEE lies in the transparency of the value added share and the associated losses of the equipment.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/overall-equipment-effectiveness] The term "Overall Equipment Efficiency" is often wrongly used as a synonym for "Overall Equipment Effectiveness".
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Measures that increase production output but incur disproportionately high costs may well be effective, but at the same time they may be inefficient and therefore economically unviable and thus unproductive.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Often, insufficient quality is not detected at the equipment that caused it.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/overall-equipment-effectiveness] In this case, it has proven effective to apply the "discovery principle," i.e., to apply an OEE reduction to the equipment where the error was discovered.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/overall-equipment-effectiveness] This removes the OEE from being purely equipment-related and turns it into a process indicator.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/overall-equipment-effectiveness] However, the OEE of a piece of equipment can of course also be optimized by making improvements to other equipment.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/overall-equipment-effectiveness] The OEE should also be a key figure that is as up-to-date as possible.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/overall-equipment-effectiveness] In this respect, the OK quantity should be determined at the latest at the end of the shift and the OEE calculated.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/overall-equipment-effectiveness] From the perspective of Process Control, the question rises how an operator can be responsible for manufacturing correct products if he cannot see whether the products are correct.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/overall-equipment-effectiveness] To highlight this problem, it is worth considering blocked products as a quality issue: after all, they were not right the first time around.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Valuable activities such as setup or maintenance will also reduce overall equipment effectiveness (OEE) at the beginning.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/overall-equipment-effectiveness] If setup activities reduce overall equipment effectiveness, there is an incentive to reduce setup times using SMED (Single-minute exchange of die).
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/overall-equipment-effectiveness] On the other hand, this also means that OEE can be increased by reducing the number of changeovers, i.e. by increasing batch sizes.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/overall-equipment-effectiveness] This would contradict the principles of lean production.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/overall-equipment-effectiveness] This highlights the importance of a clear explanation of OEE: the goal is not to be as high as possible, but to identify obstacles and then eliminate them.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/overall-equipment-effectiveness] A convention must be agreed within the company to define when downtime occurs.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Recording and justifying every second of equipment downtime is too time-consuming for most companies.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/overall-equipment-effectiveness] In practice, a recording limit of 1 to 5 minutes of equipment downtime has proven to be a pragmatic approach.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/overall-equipment-effectiveness] All downtimes of less than one minute are therefore included in the performance rate.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/overall-equipment-effectiveness] The collected data must be processed in order to obtain meaningful information.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/overall-equipment-effectiveness] This information is aimed at various target groups, such as.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Meaningful analyses prove to be the key to good decisions.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Theoretically, this is only possible with very precise figures.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/overall-equipment-effectiveness] In practice, it has been shown that correctly selected data has a greater effect in this respect than high precision.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Although tempting, OEE (as a number) is NOT suitable for comparing machines or benchmarking.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/overall-equipment-effectiveness] For similar reasons, OEE may not be applied to aggregate to Department or Plant levels.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Where multiple machines are linked together, each individual piece of equipment will display the waiting categories "No Input" (Starved) and "No output" (Blocked) in addition to the standard standstill reasons.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/overall-equipment-effectiveness] This allows upstream or downstream faults in production equipment to be identified.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/overall-equipment-effectiveness] The use of OEE requires knowledge of manufacturing environments and understanding of the underlying data.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Without this, a specific OEE number may be of little to no value.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/overall-equipment-effectiveness] OEE cannot be used to measure employee performance.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/overall-equipment-effectiveness] It is used to identify and measure equipment losses, which can then be eliminated through appropriate root cause analysis and measures.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/overall-equipment-effectiveness] Using OEE as a heuristic is not recommended.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/production-planning] Different types of production methods, such as single item manufacturing, batch production, mass production, continuous production etc. have their own type of production planning.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/production-planning] Production planning can be combined with production control into production planning and control, or it can be combined with enterprise resource planning.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/production-planning] Production planning is the future of production.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/production-planning] It can help in efficient manufacturing or setting up of a production site by facilitating required needs.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/production-planning] A production plan is made periodically for a specific time period, called the planning horizon.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/production-planning] In order to develop production plans, the production planner or production planning department needs to work closely together with the marketing department and sales department.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/production-planning] They can provide sales forecasts, or a listing of customer orders." The "work is usually selected from a variety of product types which may require different resources and serve different customers.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/production-planning] A critical factor in production planning is "the accurate estimation of the productive capacity of available resources, yet this is one of the most difficult tasks to perform well".
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/production-planning] Production planning should always take "into account material availability, resource availability and knowledge of future demand".
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/production-planning] Modern production planning methods and tools have been developed since late 19th century.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/production-planning] Under Scientific Management, the work for each man or each machine is mapped out in advance (see image).
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/production-planning] The origin of production planning back goes another century.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/production-planning] Herrmann (1996) further describes the circumstances in which new methods for internal planning and control evolved: "The first factories were quite simple and relatively small.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/production-planning] They produced a small number of products in large batches.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/production-planning] Productivity gains came from using interchangeable parts to eliminate time-consuming fitting operations.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/production-planning] Through the late 1800s, manufacturing firms were concerned with maximizing the productivity of the expensive equipment in the factory.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/production-planning] Keeping utilization high was an important objective.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/production-planning] Foremen ruled their shops, coordinating all of the activities needed for the limited number of products for which they were responsible.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/production-planning] They hired operators, purchased materials, managed production, and delivered the product.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/production-planning] They were experts with superior technical skills, and they (not a separate staff of clerks) planned production.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/production-planning] Even as factories grew, they were just bigger, not more complex.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/production-planning] About production planning Herrmann (1996) recounts that "production scheduling started simply also.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/production-planning] Schedules, when used at all, listed only when work on an order should begin or when the order is due.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/production-planning] In 1923 *Industrial Management* cited a Mr.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/production-planning] Owens who had observed: "Production planning is rapidly becoming one of the most vital necessities of management.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/production-planning] Production control is the activity of controlling the workflow in the production.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/production-planning] It is partly complementary to production planning.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/shop-floor] The **shop floor** is the production area, such as in a factory or another working space and is the floor where workers produce goods.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/shop-floor] The term "shop floor" refers to the area of a factory where production takes place.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/shop-floor] The shop floor excludes the area used or designated for administrative activities.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/shop-floor] A shop steward is an employee of a company or organization who, as a labor union member and official, represents and defends the interests of their coworkers.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/shop-floor] During the First World War, the Shop Stewards Movement brought together shop stewards from across the United Kingdom.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/shop-floor] It began with the Clyde Workers Committee, Britain's first shop stewards committee, which organized in response to the imprisonment of three of their members in 1915.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/shop-floor] Systems for managing the various components of the manufacturing process are known as shop floor control (SFC) systems.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/shop-floor] Shop floor control is one of the functions of manufacturing control; it is the process of monitoring the production activities as they happen, such as when the product is being processed, assembled, inspected, etc.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/shop-floor] It is also concerned with the shop floor inventories—short and excessive inventories that may cause losses.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/shop-floor] The manufacturing industry is significantly impacted by technological advances such as the Internet, the Web, and intelligent agents.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/shop-floor] Changing shop floor environments and customer needs are sufficed with new kinds of shop floor control systems that are web-based shop floor control systems, also called e-shop floor or i-shop floor.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/statistical-process-control] SPC must be practiced in two phases: the first phase is the initial establishment of the process, and the second phase is the regular production use of the process.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/statistical-process-control] In the second phase, a decision of the period to be examined must be made, depending upon the change in 5M&E conditions (Man, Machine, Material, Method, Movement, Environment) and wear rate of parts used in the manufacturing process (machine parts, jigs, and fixtures).
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/statistical-process-control] An advantage of SPC over other methods of quality control, such as "inspection", is that it emphasizes early detection and prevention of problems, rather than the correction of problems after they have occurred.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/statistical-process-control] In addition to reducing waste, SPC can lead to a reduction in the time required to produce the product.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/statistical-process-control] SPC makes it less likely the finished product will need to be reworked or scrapped.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/statistical-process-control] Statistical process control was pioneered by Walter A.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/statistical-process-control] Shewhart at Bell Laboratories in the early 1920s.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/statistical-process-control] Shewhart developed the control chart in 1924 and the concept of a state of statistical control.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/statistical-process-control] Statistical control is equivalent to the concept of exchangeability developed by logician William Ernest Johnson also in 1924 in his book *Logic, Part III: The Logical Foundations of Science*.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/statistical-process-control] Along with a team at AT&T that included Harold Dodge and Harry Romig he worked to put sampling inspection on a rational statistical basis as well.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/statistical-process-control] Shewhart consulted with Colonel Leslie E.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/statistical-process-control] Simon in the application of control charts to munitions manufacture at the Army's Picatinny Arsenal in 1934.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/statistical-process-control] That successful application helped convince Army Ordnance to engage AT&T's George D.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/statistical-process-control] Edwards to consult on the use of statistical quality control among its divisions and contractors at the outbreak of World War II.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/statistical-process-control] Edwards Deming invited Shewhart to speak at the Graduate School of the U.S.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/statistical-process-control] Department of Agriculture and served as the editor of Shewhart's book *Statistical Method from the Viewpoint of Quality Control* (1939), which was the result of that lecture.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/statistical-process-control] Deming was an important architect of the quality control short courses that trained American industry in the new techniques during WWII.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/statistical-process-control] The graduates of these wartime courses formed a new professional society in 1945, the American Society for Quality Control, which elected Edwards as its first president.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/statistical-process-control] Deming travelled to Japan during the Allied Occupation and met with the Union of Japanese Scientists and Engineers (JUSE) in an effort to introduce SPC methods to Japanese industry.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/statistical-process-control] Shewhart read the new statistical theories coming out of Britain, especially the work of William Sealy Gosset, Karl Pearson, and Ronald Fisher.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/statistical-process-control] However, he understood that data from physical processes seldom produced a normal distribution curve (that is, a Gaussian distribution or 'bell curve').
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/statistical-process-control] He discovered that data from measurements of variation in manufacturing did not always behave the same way as data from measurements of natural phenomena (for example, Brownian motion of particles).
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/statistical-process-control] Shewhart concluded that while every process displays variation, some processes display variation that is natural to the process ("*common*" sources of variation); these processes he described as being *in (statistical) control*.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/statistical-process-control] Other processes additionally display variation that is not present in the causal system of the process at all times ("*special*" sources of variation), which Shewhart described as *not in control*.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/statistical-process-control] Despite criticism of its use in design and development, it is well-placed to manage semi-automated data governance of high-volume data processing operations, for example in an enterprise data warehouse, or an enterprise data quality management system.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/statistical-process-control] In the 1988 Capability Maturity Model (CMM), the Software Engineering Institute suggested that SPC could be applied to software engineering processes.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/statistical-process-control] The Level 4 and Level 5 practices of the Capability Maturity Model Integration (CMMI) use this concept.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/statistical-process-control] SPC has become popular in healthcare management contexts.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/statistical-process-control] It is now recommended for use in the UK's National Health Service and used regularly.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/statistical-process-control] The application of SPC to non-repetitive, knowledge-intensive processes, such as research and development or systems engineering, has encountered skepticism and remains controversial.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/statistical-process-control] In *No Silver Bullet*, Fred Brooks points out that the complexity, conformance requirements, changeability, and invisibility of software results in inherent and essential variation that cannot be removed.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/statistical-process-control] This implies that SPC is less effective in the software development than in, e.g., manufacturing.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/statistical-process-control] In manufacturing, quality is defined as conformance to specification.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/statistical-process-control] However, no two products or characteristics are ever exactly the same, because any process contains many sources of variability.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/statistical-process-control] In mass-manufacturing, traditionally, the quality of a finished article is ensured by post-manufacturing inspection of the product.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/statistical-process-control] Any source of variation at any point of time in a process will fall into one of two classes.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/statistical-process-control] 'Common' causes are sometimes referred to as 'non-assignable', or 'normal' sources of variation.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/statistical-process-control] It refers to any source of variation that consistently acts on process, of which there are typically many.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/statistical-process-control] This type of causes collectively produce a statistically stable and repeatable distribution over time.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/statistical-process-control] 'Special' causes are sometimes referred to as 'assignable' sources of variation.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/statistical-process-control] The term refers to any factor causing variation that affects only some of the process output.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/statistical-process-control] They are often intermittent and unpredictable.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/statistical-process-control] Most processes have many sources of variation; most of them are minor and may be ignored.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/statistical-process-control] If the dominant assignable sources of variation are detected, potentially they can be identified and removed.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/statistical-process-control] When they are removed, the process is said to be 'stable'.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/statistical-process-control] When a process is stable, its variation should remain within a known set of limits.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/statistical-process-control] That is, at least, until another assignable source of variation occurs.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/statistical-process-control] For example, a breakfast cereal packaging line may be designed to fill each cereal box with 500 grams of cereal.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/statistical-process-control] Some boxes will have slightly more than 500 grams, and some will have slightly less.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/statistical-process-control] When the package weights are measured, the data will demonstrate a distribution of net weights.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/statistical-process-control] If the production process, its inputs, or its environment (for example, the machine on the line) change, the distribution of the data will change.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/statistical-process-control] For example, as the cams and pulleys of the machinery wear, the cereal filling machine may put more than the specified amount of cereal into each box.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/statistical-process-control] Although this might benefit the customer, from the manufacturer's point of view it is wasteful, and increases the cost of production.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/statistical-process-control] If the manufacturer finds the change and its source in a timely manner, the change can be corrected (for example, the cams and pulleys replaced).
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/statistical-process-control] From an SPC perspective, if the weight of each cereal box varies randomly, some higher and some lower, always within an acceptable range, then the process is considered stable.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/statistical-process-control] If the cams and pulleys of the machinery start to wear out, the weights of the cereal box might not be random.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/statistical-process-control] The degraded functionality of the cams and pulleys may lead to a non-random linear pattern of increasing cereal box weights.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/statistical-process-control] If, however, all the cereal boxes suddenly weighed much more than average because of an unexpected malfunction of the cams and pulleys, this would be considered a special cause variation.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/statistical-process-control] The advent of Industry 4.0 has broadened the scope of statistical process control from traditional manufacturing processes to modern cyber-physical and data-driven systems.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/statistical-process-control] (2024) note that SPC now plays a role in monitoring complex, high-dimensional, and often automated processes that characterise Industry 4.0 environments, including the use of machine learning and artificial intelligence (AI) models in production settings.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/statistical-process-control] One emerging line of research applies SPC techniques to artificial neural networks and other machine learning models.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/statistical-process-control] Instead of directly monitoring product quality, the focus is on the detection of unreliable behavior of AI systems.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/statistical-process-control] For example, nonparametric multivariate control charts have been proposed to track shifts in the distribution of neural network embeddings, allowing detection of nonstationarity and concept drift without requiring labelled data.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/statistical-process-control] This enables real-time monitoring of deployed AI systems in industrial contexts.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/statistical-process-control] Eliminating assignable (special) sources of variation, so that the process is stable.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/statistical-process-control] Monitoring the ongoing production process, assisted by the use of control charts, to detect significant changes of mean or variation.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/statistical-process-control] The proper implementation of SPC has been limited, in part due to a lack of statistical expertise at many organizations.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/statistical-process-control] The data from measurements of variations at points on the process map is monitored using control charts.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/statistical-process-control] Control charts attempt to differentiate "assignable" ("special") sources of variation from "common" sources.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/statistical-process-control] "Common" sources, because they are an expected part of the process, are of much less concern to the manufacturer than "assignable" sources.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/statistical-process-control] Using control charts is a continuous activity, ongoing over time.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/statistical-process-control] When the process does not trigger any of the control chart "detection rules" for the control chart, it is said to be "stable".
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/statistical-process-control] A process capability analysis may be performed on a stable process to predict the ability of the process to produce "conforming product" in the future.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/statistical-process-control] A stable process can be demonstrated by a process signature that is free of variances outside of the capability index.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/statistical-process-control] A process signature is the plotted points compared with the capability index.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/statistical-process-control] When the process triggers any of the control chart "detection rules", (or alternatively, the process capability is low), other activities may be performed to identify the source of the excessive variation.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/statistical-process-control] The tools used in these extra activities include: Ishikawa diagram, designed experiments, and Pareto charts.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/statistical-process-control] Designed experiments are a means of objectively quantifying the relative importance (strength) of sources of variation.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/statistical-process-control] Once the sources of (special cause) variation are identified, they can be minimized or eliminated.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/statistical-process-control] Steps to eliminating a source of variation might include: development of standards, staff training, error-proofing, and changes to the process itself or its inputs.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/statistical-process-control] When monitoring many processes with control charts, it is sometimes useful to calculate quantitative measures of the stability of the processes.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/statistical-process-control] These metrics can then be used to identify/prioritize the processes that are most in need of corrective actions.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/statistical-process-control] These metrics can also be viewed as supplementing the traditional process capability metrics.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/statistical-process-control] Several metrics have been proposed, as described in Ramirez and Runger.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/statistical-process-control] Control charts are based on a time-ordered sequence of observations $X_{1},X_{2},\dots ,X_{t}$ of a process characteristic.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/statistical-process-control] The monitored characteristic can be single observations, averages of samples or batches, ranges, variances, or residuals from a fitted model, depending on the application.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/statistical-process-control] ${\text{UCL}}=\mu _{0}+k\sigma ,\quad {\text{LCL}}=\mu _{0}-k\sigma ,$ where $\mu _{0}$ and $\sigma$ denote the in-control mean and standard deviation, and k is commonly chosen as 3 (the "three-sigma rule").
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/statistical-process-control] An observation $X_{t}$ falling outside the interval $[{\text{LCL}},{\text{UCL}}]$ signals a potential out-of-control condition.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/statistical-process-control] Variants such as the cumulative sum (CUSUM) chart and the exponentially weighted moving average charts (EWMA chart) are used to improve sensitivity to small or persistent shifts.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/statistical-process-control] In many applications, however, the assumption of independent observations is violated, for example in autocorrelated time series.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/statistical-process-control] In such cases, the conventional control limits may produce excessive false alarms.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/statistical-process-control] A common solution is to fit a time series model (e.g., ARIMA) and construct a residual control chart, where the model residuals ${\hat {\varepsilon }}_{t}=X_{t}-{\hat {X}}_{t}$ are monitored instead, or to adjust the control limits accordingly.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/statistical-process-control] Because the residuals are designed to be approximately independent and identically distributed, standard control chart theory can be applied to them.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/statistical-process-control] Adjusted control limits or model-based approaches are therefore required when processes exhibit dependence.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/work-order] A **work order** is usually a task or a job for a customer, that can be scheduled or assigned to someone.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/work-order] Such an order may be from a customer request or created internally within the organization.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/work-order] Work orders may also be created as follow ups to inspections or audits.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/work-order] A work order may be for products or services.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/work-order] In a manufacturing environment, a work order is converted from a sales order to show that work is about to begin on the manufacture, building or engineering of the products requested by the customer.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/work-order] In a service environment, a work order can be equivalent to a service order where the WO records the location, date and time the service is carried out and the nature of work that is done.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/work-order] The type of personnel (e.g. job position) may also be listed on the WO.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/work-order] A rate (e.g. $/hr, $/week) and also the total number of hours worked and total value is also shown on the work order.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/work-order] A work order may be a maintenance or repair request from students, faculty or staff in a university.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/work-order] Orders received from outside an organization are often dispatched (reviewed and scheduled) before being executed.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/work-order] Work orders may be for preventive maintenance.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/work-order] Contractors may use a single job work order and invoice form that contains the customer information, describes the work performed, lists charges for material and labor, and can be given to the customer as an invoice.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/work-order] A job order is an internal document extensively used by projects-based, manufacturing, building and fabrication businesses.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/work-order] A job order may be for products and/or services.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/work-order] In a manufacturing environment, a job order is used to signal the start of a manufacturing process and will most probably be linked to a bill of material.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/work-order] In a service environment, a job order cannot be the equivalent to a work or service order where the job order records the location, date and time the service is carried out and the nature of service that was carried out, the work order does not.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/work-order] The type of personnel (e.g. job position) may also be listed on the job order.
[src:manufacturing-execution-systems/work-order] A rate (e.g. $/hr, $/week) and also the total number of hours worked and total value is also shown.
